              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3zp3wm11/manifest/annotation/p7",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>3</p>\n            <p>pander to the irregular wishes of a majority. His proclamation is<lb/> the exponent\n                of that excellent provision in the American Constitution,<lb/> which forms its\n                brightest ornament, but of which zealots are now<lb/> striving to divert it. Not\n                they who tender divine adoration to the man<lb/> of <placeName>Nazareth</placeName>\n                are exclusively recommended to beseech the living God for<lb/> the triumph of\n                rightful authority over usurpation but the people at large, so that<lb/> the\n                entreats of a whole nation ascending the throne of grace may bring<lb/> down\n                plentiful blessings upon our afflicted country. Such, or the like,<lb/> are his\n                words; very dissimilar my Brethren! from those of some high functionaries,<lb/>\n                whose narrow views debar them from discerning beyond the pale<lb/> of their\n                religion, an object worthy of any consideration. In confor<lb/>mity therefore with\n                so discreet a summons, we will again pour<lb/> out our souls before the Omnipotent\n                    <add>עושה במלאכה ואחת מחזקת השלחבאחת ידו</add><lb/> “Peradventure will He think\n                on us, that we perish not” <del>Yet</del> But, the<lb/> prayer of freedom-loving\n                Americans must be accompanied by deeds of<lb/> abnegation. I will repeat it:\n                    <del>That</del> Yonder sturdy man who in these<lb/> stirring times <hi\n                    rend=\"underline\">inactively</hi> contemplates the perilous state of the\n                    <del>country</del> Republic,<lb/> though he bow the head as a bulrush, mistakes\n                the aim of his exist<lb/>=ence. When around the noblest monument of human\n                wisdom,<lb/> fall destroyers have gathered, let the vigorous, like the ancient\n                Hebrews<lb/> labour with one hand in the work of reconstruction, and wield in\n                the<lb/> other a repelling sword. <add>אין סומכין על הנס</add></p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3zp3wm11/canvas/p7"
                }
              ]
            }
