              "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3zp3wm11/canvas/p8/annopage",
              "type": "AnnotationPage",
              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3zp3wm11/manifest/annotation/p8",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>4</p>\n            <p>the God of battles <del>of</del> will lead to victory. But if the patriotic\n                ardour<lb/> that seemed to burn in every breast, when the national escutcheon\n                was<lb/> first tarnished, has been quenched by the Liuthean<add>?</add> water of\n                egotism;<lb/> if the memory of the past achievements and past glory contrasted\n                with<lb/> the present humiliation does not arouse <del>not</del> in our midst the\n                    <persName>Leonidas</persName>, that<lb/> will struggle for the maintenance of\n                this peerless Union; if the<lb/> taunts of the ungenerous foreigner, and the\n                sardonic smile of despots,<lb/> are incapable of inspiriting <hi rend=\"underline\"\n                    >all</hi> to energetic actions, the entreaties<lb/> offered this day will fail\n                to <sic>propitrate</sic> the assistance of the Most High.<lb/>\n                <add>בעון בצעו קצפתי ואכהו הסתר ואקצף וילך שובב בדרך לבו</add>, is a wise aphorism\n                of <placeName>Israel's</placeName> ancient Teachers.<lb/> “We must not rely on\n                miracles” Nothing is impossible to Him<lb/> who inspired a\n                    <persName>Gideon</persName>, and by three hundred of the faithful, put to\n                flight<lb/> the redoubtable <del>best</del> army of <placeName>Midian</placeName>,\n                but while <del>we</del> it behooves us to beseech<lb/> Him and confide in his\n                support for the ultimate success of a<lb/> righteous cause we must labour for our\n                salvation. <sic>we</sic> must render ourselves deserving of it by prefer=<lb/>=ring\n                to <hi rend=\"underline\">individual</hi> promotion, national honor, national\n                    <del>greatness</del> Unity,<lb/> national peace. Shall I now point out, how the\n                pursuing of<lb/> the opposite course, became the bane of\n                    <placeName>America</placeName>,? how personal<lb/> ambition becomes the vampire\n                that fed on her life's blood? How self-<lb/>interest gave birth to parasites who\n                scampered with the rich spoil of<lb/> their unsuspecting host? Shall I say, that\n                even at this hour, when</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3zp3wm11/canvas/p8"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
